 f*H H 4a'st. 1 82% 82%\nN Y NH4cH 4%s 67 4 93% 93%\nV\n1 k y\nFINANCIAL.\nBUSINESS OUTLOOK,\nMUCH IMPROVED\nA. B. A. Journal Reports\nGains Beneath Surface\nWhich Indicate Upturn.\nThe past month has materially im\nproved the business outlook, but the\ngains have not been so much on the\nsurface as beneath it. says the Amer\nican Bankers' Association Journal. The\nreview says:\n\u201cThe prolonged decline in business\nactivity has now given way to a hori\nzontal trend and the conviction seems\nwarranted that the bottom of the de\npression has been reached. Os course,\nthis would not preclude the possibility\nof a slowing down at the end of the\nyear, but that is a normal seasonal\nmovement.\n\u201cUnquestionably the gains apparent\non the surface will come slowly. Un\nemployment is one of the major prob\nlems and it is doubtful whether this\nwill improve much during the Winter\nmonths, although the Nation-wide ef\nforts to prevent distress and to enlarge\nemployment will check it from becom\ning worse. Unemployment is only one\nof the many problems that must he\nsolved before the country returns to\nreal prosperity, and hopes for a quick\nrecovery have been succeeded by confi\ndence in a slow but sure recovery.\n\u201cBelow the surface of business ac\ntivity there have been drastic readjust- J\nmenus going on for many months. Some\nof them have already been completed\nand are being reflected in a speeding\nup of current operations on a sound\nbasts. In the field of distribution, there\nhas been a definite improvement In\nsales, and this is causing wholesalers\nand Jobbers to buy more freely. One\nof the most encouraging developments\nat the present time is that basic com\nmodities are beginning to move in both\ndomestic and foreign trade and prices\nhave become more stabilized, proving\nthat the users of raw materials hav\u00bb\nconfidence both in the business outlook\nand in the price level.\n\u201cConsiderable comment has been\nheard about the recent Improvement In\nthe textiles, with the cotton goods In\ndustry eliminating night work and ad-\njusting production to normal demand,\nthe purchasing of raw silk being un\nusually active and the reports from the\nwoolen trade brighter than for many\nmonths. It will be recalled that the\ntextile Industries led the way in the\nbusiness recovery after the 1921 depres\nsion, which causes current developments\nto be followed with more than usual\ninterest.\n\"The marked liquidation in brokers\u2019\nloans that continued during the past\nmonth, and the strong and liquid con\ndition of the banking system generally,\nare most impressive favorable develop\nments. No country ever went \u2018broke\u2019\nby having its citizens pay off their bor-\nrowings, or is there any more certain\nway in which to build the foundation\nfor expansion later on.\u201d\nNATIONAL ADVERTISERS\nWILL STRESS PRODUCTS\nBr the Associated Press.\nThe majority of national advertisers\nare firm believers that curtailed buying\nperiods are the proper time to stress\ntheir products.\nThis fact Is brought out in a poll of\n256 companies conaucted among mem\nbers of the Association of National\nAdvertisers to determine their intentions\nwith regard to appropriations for the\ncoming year. Os this total 121 stated\nthey would repeat the present year's\nappropriations in 1931; 60 declared they\nwoulds, increase next year's appropria-\ntions over the current year, and 14 said\nthey would decrease their commitments.\nSixty-one were unable to give figures.\nMARYLAND TOBACCO SALES.\nBALTIMORE. November 10 (Spe\ncial).\u2014Both receipts and sales of Mary\nland leaf tobacco showed declines the\nformer totaling 655 hogsheads, while\nsales of 548 hogsheads were reported,\nleaving a stock In State tobacco ware\nhouses, and 34 hogsheads of ground\nleaves.\nMarket steady at the following quo\ntations per 100 pounds: Inferior, 6.00a\n10.00; sound common, 10.00a22.00; good\ncommon, 22.50a32.00; medium, 32.50a\n40.00; good to fine red, 40.50a53.00;\nfancy, 53.50a54.00. Seconds\u2014Common\nto good common, 10.00a25.00: medium\n25.50a30.00; good to fine. 35.50a45.00\nground leaves, nominal; upper countv\nBurley, 7.00a4C.00.\nFOREIGN EXCHANGE.\n(Quotation* furnished b\u00bb W B Hibbs Co\nNominal sold Selling check*\nvalue. today.\nLondon, pouno J4.B6SS $4.8511\nParts, franc 3.91%c 3.93 c\nBrussels, belga 13.91 c 13.94%c\nBerlin, mark 33.82 c 23.83%c\nRome, lira 5.26 c 5.23,*,c\nZurich, franc 19.3 c 19.40' ,e\nAthens, drachma. 13c\nMadrid, peseta 19.3 c\nVienna, schilling. 14.07 c\nBudapest, pengo. 17.49 c\nPrague, crown (nom.i 2 964 c 3.96!1c\nWarsaw, zloty 11.22 c\nCopenhagen, crown 26.8 c 26.75%c\nOslo, crown... 26 8c 26.75%e\nStockholm, crown.... 26.5 c 28.81 %c\nAmerican tanners supply more than\n85 per cent of the patent leather sold\nin Shanghai.\nSales. High. Low Close.\nNY NH&H cv db 6s 22 117% 116% 117\nNY NH H clt 6a. 3 106 106 106\nNY O&W Ist 45'92 6 45% 45 45\nNY Rys Inc 6s 65.. 5 3 3 3\n+NY Rys6s A 65... 5 62% 52% 52%\nNY S&W gn 5s '43. 5 60 60 60\nNY W&B 4%5'46.. 14 85% 85 85\nNorf South 65'41.. 4 37% 37 37\nNor Pacific 3s 2047 7 68 66% 66%\nNor Pacific 45'97.. 23 94 93% 93%\nNor Pac 4%s 2047. 2 97% 97% 97%\nNor Pac r 1 6s 2047.116 111% 111% 111%\nPenn 4%s \"63 9 100% 100 100\nPenn 4%s '7O 28 98% 97% 9g%\nPenn gen 6s *68.... 15 109% 109 109%\nPenna 6s \u201964 18 104% 103% 103%\nPenn 6%s '36 10 109% 108 109%\nFere M Ist 65'56.. 13 103% 103% 103%\nPhilippine RR 4s. 1 23 23 23\nPCC&St L6s A.. 3 109 109 109\nPCC&StL6sB.. 2 108V* 108 108%\nPor R L&P 7%5'46 4 108 108 108\nRead gen 4%s A'97 1 100 100 100\nRead Jerf'en 4s'sl 1 94% 94)4 94%\nRio Gr VV Ist 4s '39 5 92% 92% 92%\nRlAr L 4%s \u201934 21 100% 100% 100%\nSt L Ir M'ot 6s'3l. 7 100% 100% 100%\nStL IM RAG 4a 100 100 99% 99%\nStL&SFIn4SA. 17 85 84% 84%\nSt L&S F 4%5'7\u00ab. 58 83 81% 81%\nSt LSVV cv 4s'S3. 1 100 100 100\nSt LS W Ist 4S'B9. 1 90% 90% 90%\nStPAKCSL4%s 1 98 98 98\nSan A&A P4s 43. 11 94 93 93\nSeab ALrf 4s 49.. 12 22% 20% 20